Generic components don't honor lifestyle types set programmatically. If I use: container.AddComponentWithLifestyle("comp", typeof(IRepository<>), typeof(RepositoryNotMarkedAsTransient<>), LifestyleType.Transient);
but don't attach the [Castle.Core.Transient] tag to the class "RepositoryNotMarkedAsTransient" then the component is created as a singleton by the DefaultGenericHandler.
I've attached the test files from Windsor with a failing test added which illustrates the problem. I've also attached a proposed fix. I'm not too familiar with the code, so the fix might be right off base, but it may also help you identify what does need fixing. The fix is in Castle.MicroKernel.Handlers.DefaultGenericHandler.cs, method GetSubHandler.
